Prey mortality

When prey die during an experiment due to other causes than predation, estimated feeding rates can be biased even when correcting for prey depletion with a dynamical prediction model. The number of available prey declines faster than predicted by feeding only. Instead, the number of available prey \(N(t)\) (i.e.Â not eaten and not dead) can be modelled with an additional, linear mortality term \[\frac{dN}{dt}=-F(N)P-mN\] where \(F(N)\) is a functional response describing per-capita feeding rate, \(P\) is predator number, and \(m\) is the preyâs mortality rate.

Statistically, it can be difficult to tease apart functional response parameters such as attack rate \(a\) and mortality rate \(m\), when only data from feeding trials are used. Parameter estimates tend to be correlated. As an extreme case, consider the linear type 1 FR \(F(N)=aN\). Here, it is impossible to distinguish between attack and mortality rate, as the model reduces to \(\frac{dN}{dt}=-(a+m)N\). Ideally, control treatments without predators are performed to estimate mortality rate. For \(P=0\), the prediction model reduces to \[\frac{dN}{dt}=-mN\] We are able to fit both the predator and the control treatment data in one joint statistical model. Here, the function Type3GenH_mort_dyn(N0,P0,Time,b,h,q,m) includes a generalized type 3 FR with mortality term \[\frac{dN}{dt}=-\frac{bN^{1+q}}{1+bhN^{1+q}} P-mN\] It predicts the number or eaten or dead prey \(\hat{N}_E=N_0-N_T\). A column \(P_0\) for predator number (\(P_0=0\) for control, \(P_0>0\) for predator treatments) is required in the dataframe. This model also includes the type 2 and type 3 FRs by fixing the exponent \(q\) at 0 Type3GenH_mort_dyn(N0,P0,Time,b,h,0,m) or at 1 Type3GenH_mort_dyn(N0,P0,Time,b,h,1,m), respectively. Because of the mortality term, neither of them has an analytical solution and model predictions are computed numerically.

Archer et al.Â (2019) Dryad

Minimal example

library(BayesFR)
library(cowplot) # ggplot grids
df = df_Archer_et_al_2019_JAE
head(df)
  N0 NE P0 Time           Predator       Prey Temperature    Setting Year
1  1  0  1   24 Limnophora_riparia Simuliidae         5.3 laboratory 2013
2  1  0  1   24 Limnophora_riparia Simuliidae         5.3 laboratory 2013
3  1  0  1   24 Limnophora_riparia Simuliidae         5.3 laboratory 2013
4  1  0  1   24 Limnophora_riparia Simuliidae         5.3 laboratory 2013
5  2  0  1   24 Limnophora_riparia Simuliidae         5.3 laboratory 2013
6  2  1  1   24 Limnophora_riparia Simuliidae         5.3 laboratory 2013
df = subset(df, Year=="2015")
df = subset(df, Setting=="laboratory")
df = subset(df, Predator=="Limnophora_riparia" | Predator=="control")
df = subset(df, Temperature==9.6)

ggplot(df, aes(N0, NE)) +
  geom_jitter(width=0.0, height=0.05, alpha=0.6, size=2.5) +
  facet_wrap(~Predator)
FR.formula = bf( NE | trials(N0) ~ Type3GenH_mort_dyn(N0,P0,1.0,a,h,0.0,m)/N0,
                 a+h+m~1,
                 nl = TRUE)
FR.priors  = c(prior(exponential(1.0), nlpar="a", lb=0),
               prior(exponential(1.0), nlpar="h", lb=0),
               prior(exponential(1.0), nlpar="m", lb=0))
fit.1 = brm(FR.formula,
            family   = binomial(link="identity"),
            prior    = FR.priors,
            data     = df,
            cores    = 4,
            stanvars = stanvar(scode=Type3GenH_mort_dyn_code, block="functions")
)
expose_functions(fit.1, vectorize=TRUE)
summary(fit.1)

  Links: mu = identity

         a ~ 1
         h ~ 1
         m ~ 1

and Tail_ESS are effective sample size measures, and Rhat is the potential
scale reduction factor on split chains (at convergence, Rhat = 1).
df.predator = subset(df, P0==1)
p1 = plot(conditional_effects(fit.1,
                              effects="N0",
                              conditions=data.frame(P0=1),
                              int_conditions=data.frame(N0=1:16)),
          points=FALSE, plot=FALSE)
p1 = p1[[1]] +
  geom_jitter(aes(x=N0, y=NE),
              alpha = 0.5, width=0.0, height=0.05, size=2,
              inherit.aes = FALSE,
              data = df.predator) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim=c(0,48), ylim=c(0,7)) +
  ggtitle("Predator")

df.control = subset(df, P0==0)
p2 = plot(conditional_effects(fit.1,
                              effects="N0",
                              conditions=data.frame(P0=0)),
          points=FALSE, plot=FALSE)
p2 = p2[[1]] +
  geom_jitter(aes(x=N0, y=NE),
              alpha = 0.5, width=0.0, height=0.05, size=2,
              inherit.aes = FALSE,
              data = df.control) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim=c(0,48), ylim=c(0,7)) +
  ggtitle("Control")

plot_grid(p1, p2, ncol=2)

Continuous predictor

df = df_Archer_et_al_2019_JAE
df = subset(df, Year=="2015")
df = subset(df, Predator=="Limnophora_riparia" | Predator=="control")
ggplot(df, aes(N0, NE, color=Temperature)) +
  geom_jitter(width=0.1, height=0.2, alpha=0.5, size=2) +
  facet_wrap(~Predator)
FR.formula = bf( NE | trials(N0) ~ Type3GenH_mort_dyn(N0,P0,1.0,a,h,0.0,m)/N0,
                 nlf(a~exp(a0+a1*(Temperature-10.0)/(8.62*10^(-5)*(Temperature+273.15)*283.15))),
                 nlf(h~exp(h0+h1*(Temperature-10.0)/(8.62*10^(-5)*(Temperature+273.15)*283.15))),
                 nlf(m~exp(m0+m1*(Temperature-10.0)/(8.62*10^(-5)*(Temperature+273.15)*283.15))),
                 a0+a1+h0+h1+m0+m1~1,
                 nl = TRUE)
FR.priors  = c(prior(normal(0,3), nlpar="a0"),
               prior(normal(0,1), nlpar="a1"),
               prior(normal(0,3), nlpar="h0"),
               prior(normal(0,1), nlpar="h1"),
               prior(normal(0,3), nlpar="m0"),
               prior(normal(0,1), nlpar="m1"))
fit.2 = brm(FR.formula,
            family   = binomial(link="identity"),
            prior    = FR.priors,
            data     = df,
            cores    = 4,
            stanvars = stanvar(scode=Type3GenH_mort_dyn_code, block="functions")
)
expose_functions(fit.2, vectorize=TRUE)
summary(fit.2)

Continuous and categorical predictor

FR.formula = bf( NE | trials(N0) ~ Type3GenH_mort_dyn(N0,P0,1.0,a,h,0.0,m)/N0,
                 nlf(a~exp(a0+a1*(Temperature-10.0)/(8.62*10^(-5)*(Temperature+273.15)*283.15))),
                 nlf(h~exp(h0+h1*(Temperature-10.0)/(8.62*10^(-5)*(Temperature+273.15)*283.15))),
                 nlf(m~exp(m0+m1*(Temperature-10.0)/(8.62*10^(-5)*(Temperature+273.15)*283.15))),
                 a0+h0+m0 ~ 0+Setting,
                 a1+h1+m1 ~ 1,
                 nl = TRUE)
FR.priors  = c(prior(normal(0,3), nlpar="a0"),
               prior(normal(0,1), nlpar="a1"),
               prior(normal(0,3), nlpar="h0"),
               prior(normal(0,1), nlpar="h1"),
               prior(normal(0,3), nlpar="m0"),
               prior(normal(0,1), nlpar="m1"))
fit.3 = brm(FR.formula,
            family   = binomial(link="identity"),
            prior    = FR.priors,
            data     = df,
            cores    = 4,
            stanvars = stanvar(scode=Type3GenH_mort_dyn_code, block="functions")
)
expose_functions(fit.3, vectorize=TRUE)
